english:
  title: A Letter to Scholar Lee
  author: Im Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    That writing is difficult need not be said—yet it cannot be mastered through study alone. For the finest and most vital spirit fills one's being and overflows into countenance, manifests in speech without conscious effort. Should one truly cultivate this spirit, even without ever taking brush to paper in formal study, one's writing shall naturally grow wondrous.

    To cultivate such spirit requires traversing famous mountains and great rivers, seeking the extraordinary tales and magnificent vistas of all under heaven—without this, the aspirations of one's breast cannot expand. Thus Su Ziyou declared: "Through mountains I beheld the heights of Zhongnan, Song, and Hua; through waters, the vastness of the Yellow River; through people, the eminence of Ouyang Gong and General Han. Only then did I exhaust the great spectacles of the world."

    With utmost respect, I contemplate how Your Excellency, possessed of stalwart words and unwavering integrity, stands alone across two dynasties as the arbiter of letters. The finest scholars of the age all revere and take you as their master. I have long harbored the wish to approach your gate with respectful heart, to assume the role of humble disciple among your learned followers, and thereafter retire to perfect my own writing. Yet since calamity befell, I have dwelt far from the capital these many years, and my lowly station grows ever more distant and obscure. My shoulders have not brushed your threshold, my name has not reached the ears of great men. I fear being buried in obscurity without awakening to my greater purpose.

    Recently I heard that Your Excellency deigned to speak of my humble work and commanded it be submitted. At this, I ventured to think: How fortunate to offer my meager skills before you, to behold the radiance of a sage, to hear words by which I may measure myself. Though I have not witnessed the heights of Zhongnan, Song, and Hua, nor the vastness of the Yellow River, nor the magnificence of Ouyang and General Han, this alone suffices—I harbor no regret.

    I respectfully record and present to you my essay titled "The Record of Yizhai." Should you deign to offer but a word of praise or criticism, no fortune in all my remaining days could surpass it. I humbly submit this letter.
  footnotes:
    - Su Ziyou (蘇子由, 1059-1112) was the brother of the famous poet-statesman Su Shi; his reflections on cultivating one's spirit through experience of nature deeply influenced Korean literary thought.
    - The "five famous mountains" referenced (Zhongnan, Song, and Hua) and the Yellow River were archetypal symbols of natural grandeur in classical Chinese aesthetics, representing the ultimate education of the spirit.
    - Ouyang Gong refers to Ouyang Xiu (歐陽修, 1007-1072), the preeminent Song dynasty writer and statesman; General Han likely refers to Han Qi (韓琦, 1008-1075), another prominent Song official.
    - The work addresses a prestigious government scholar (學士) during a period of political upheaval, with the author seeking literary patronage and recognition after a period of estrangement from the capital.
